      <memberdef kind="function" id="group__arch-timing_1gacc1ed8d949f694a1d39e389334caf971" prot="public" static="yes" const="no" explicit="no" inline="yes" virt="non-virtual">
        <type><ref refid="stdint_8h_1a2095b9bffea4b2656950c6c0419edbf1" kindref="member">uint64_t</ref></type>
        <definition>static uint64_t arch_k_cycle_get_64</definition>
        <argsstring>(void)</argsstring>
        <name>arch_k_cycle_get_64</name>
        <param>
          <type>void</type>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>As for <ref refid="group__arch-timing_1ga9ee9f897ec750957de45bf8d43349d5e" kindref="member">arch_k_cycle_get_32()</ref>, but with a 64 bit return value. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Not all timer hardware has a 64 bit timer, this needs to be implemented only if CONFIG_TIMER_HAS_64BIT_CYCLE_COUNTER is set.</para>
<para><simplesect kind="see"><para><ref refid="group__arch-timing_1ga9ee9f897ec750957de45bf8d43349d5e" kindref="member">arch_k_cycle_get_32()</ref></para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>The current cycle time. This should count up monotonically through the full 64 bit space, wrapping at 2^64-1. Hardware with fewer bits of precision in the timer is generally not expected to implement this API. </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
